{{Quote|They have Master Yoda's species listed as Lannik, and his midi-chlorian count at 4 million. That's just ridiculous!|Coleman Trebor|<ref name="holo">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|50|jediwatch/1344_2.html|Jedi TradeChips Spark Controversy}}</ref>
}}'''Jedi TradeChips''' were a line of [[tradechip]]s produced by the [[Spotts TradeChip Company]] in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]]. These were the first tradechips to depict famous members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]]. Much like sports tradechips, they contained small [[Hologram/Legends|holograms]] of the Jedi depicted, biographical information, and vital statistics (though rather than races won and goals scored, the chips listed confirmed kills and [[Midi-chlorian/Legends|midi-chlorian]] count.)<ref name="holo">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|50|jediwatch/1344_2.html|Jedi TradeChips Spark Controversy}}</ref>

Although Spotts' marketing manager, [[Wil Jhonems]], claimed that the tradechips were intended to hold famous Jedi up as role models for [[Younglings/Legends|young children]], they were controversial at the time. Most Jedi, such as [[Jedi Master/Legends|Master]] [[Coleman Trebor/Legends|Coleman Trebor]], felt that merchandising the Jedi was disrespectful towards [[The Force/Legends|the Force]], as Jedi were meant to be servants rather than celebrities. As the Jedi refused to cooperate with the production of this unlicensed merchandising by granting access to the [[Jedi Archives/Legends|Jedi Archives]], many of the statistics were inaccurate.<ref name="holo" />

[[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]], for example, was identified as a [[Lannik (species)/Legends|Lannik]] rather than his [[Yoda's species/Legends|true species]], and given an inaccurate midi-chlorian count of four million. Trebor also pointed out that if the information had been accurate, the Jedi's enemies would have been able to use the information against them.<ref name="holo" />

Though the [[Jedi High Council/Legends|Jedi Council]] tried to halt production of the tradechips, Spotts intended to release a second set (with updated information) in the near future.<ref name="holo" />

